`crates/ctx-verify/src` is the ctx-verify crate: it runs a fixed battery of cargo/clippy/doc/test/script checks against the workspace and emits one capped, token-frugal JSON (or terse text) verification report. Depending on it means invoking `cli::run` (or the `main` binary) and getting back a `Report` whose shape is a stable wire contract shared with the spec's audit-report family — consumers should treat `model.rs`'s field names as an external interface.

The subtree is layered: `runner.rs` is the process-spawn boundary (`Runner` trait + `ProcRunner`), `checks.rs` is pure orchestration over that trait (the static `SPECS` list, per-check `Parser` fns, three-way skip/error/fail split), `parse.rs` turns raw tool output into `Diagnostic`s, `model.rs` defines the capped/truncated report structs with hand-written `Serialize` impls, `error.rs` is the shared `CheckError` taxonomy, and `cli.rs`/`main.rs` wire argv to `checks::run_selected` and render the result. A typical change to add a check starts in `checks.rs` (new `Spec` + `Parser`) and may need a new parser fn in `parse.rs`; a change to the diagnostic fields must touch `parse.rs`, `model.rs`, and `cli.rs`'s JSON/terse renderers together.

Cross-cutting invariants: diagnostics are always capped at `max` per check with the overflow recorded in `truncated`, never silently dropped; `Report`'s top-level `Status` prioritizes Errored > Fail > Pass (Skipped never affects it); and any check that fails with zero parsed diagnostics still produces a non-empty synthesized `"exit"` diagnostic via `checks.rs`'s `failure_hint` fallback, so no check-failure is ever silent — but this fallback only fires on nonzero exit, not when a parser mismatches a successful, warning-emitting run (a live coupling risk between `parse.rs`'s expected formats and the actual clippy/rustdoc/script output).

No `intent.md` is present for this directory.